tyle="font-family:MinionPro-Regular; font-size:12pt">al (Labour) model concentrated </span><span style="font-family:MinionPro-Regular; font-size:12pt">on re-launching previously unsuccessful urban schools, while the current (Coalition) model has been offered as a way forward for all state schools, though with much higher take-up rates, both in Surrey and nationally, among secondary than among primary or </span><span style="font-family:MinionPro-Regular; font-size:12pt">special schools.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">52 </span><span style="font-family:MinionPro-Regular; font-size:12pt">of the 380 state schools in Surrey </span><span style="font-family:MinionPro-Regular; font-size:12pt">have converted to academy s</span><span style="font-family:MinionPro-Regular; font-size:12pt">tatus</span><span style="font-family:MinionPro-Regular; font-size:12pt">.  A</span><span style="font-family:MinionPro-Regular; font-size:12pt"> further 11 </span><span style="font-family:MinionPro-Regular; font-size:12pt">are currently involved in</span><span style="font-family:MinionPro-Regular; font-size:12pt"> the conversion process</span><span style="font-family:MinionPro-Regular; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:MinionPro-Regular; font-size:12pt">There are a number of other schools that are actively considering and consulting regarding conversi</span><span style="font-family:MinionPro-Regular; font-size:12pt">on to academy status.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">27 secondary schools are now academies, which is just over 50% of all the secondary school in Surrey.  </span><span style="font-fami