s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to academy status during the year then these works </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are still</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> carried</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> out.  There is no commitment to funding any works at a school unless it is in the current year’s planned programme as there is no visibility of budgets for future years.  If the school wish to have any high priority maintenance works carried out post conv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ersion then they can make a bid to the Department for Education (DfE) for Capital Maintenance Funding.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">During the conversion process schools frequently request the inclusion of all identified aspects of the conditions updates to be included in the Commerc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ial Transfer Agreement.  For the reasons stated above this is not agreed.  However there is an issue for the Local Authority with schools that are being sponsored and may be opposed to this process, as they are not going through the conversion through choi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ce.  If relationships between the sponsoring trust and the school are not strong late identification by the sponsoring trust of unresolved or outstanding maintenance issues can result in protracted negotiations for inclusion of works in the C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ommercial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ran</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-